20
00:01:09,200 --> 00:01:13,920
So is it a Zimbabwe, B Switzerland or C Bolivia?

21
00:01:13,920 --> 00:01:16,239
I would guess Zimbabwe.

22
00:01:16,239 --> 00:01:19,280
Well we'll find out the answer at the end of the programme.

23
00:01:19,280 --> 00:01:23,599
Now Hannah, you've been finding out about some of the benefits of being a polyglot.

24
00:01:24,399 --> 00:01:31,280
Yes Neil, there's been lots of research about how knowing more than one language can change your brain.

25
00:01:31,280 --> 00:01:34,000
And this might have some health benefits too.

26
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:37,439
At What in the World we spoke to Professor Frederick Liegeau,

27
00:01:37,439 --> 00:01:41,439
who's a cognitive neuroscientist at University College London.

28
00:01:42,319 --> 00:01:47,679
Babies, even before they speak, have to tune into the languages around them to make sense out of what

29
00:01:47,679 --> 00:01:48,719
people say to them.

30
00:01:48,719 --> 00:01:51,599
And then when children start to speak several languages,

31
00:01:51,599 --> 00:01:56,000
they have to focus on one language and ignore another one where they're speaking.

32
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,359
They also have to be able to switch from one language to the other,

33
00:01:59,359 --> 00:02:01,439
depending on who they're speaking to.

34
00:02:01,439 --> 00:02:04,959
Later on in age, when adults have dementia,

35
00:02:04,959 --> 00:02:09,280
they seem to show symptoms later when they're bilinguals as opposed to monolinguals.

36
00:02:09,759 --> 00:02:14,719
Within that juggling, several languages has helped them really boost this brain efficiency,

37
00:02:14,719 --> 00:02:16,560
which is a great advantage.

38
00:02:16,560 --> 00:02:17,919
It's like a brain workout.

39
00:02:18,079 --> 00:02:24,560
Frederick explains that babies who grow up learning more than one language have to tune into the

40
00:02:24,560 --> 00:02:25,599
languages around them.

41
00:02:26,239 --> 00:02:28,479
They have to listen to each language.

42
00:02:28,479 --> 00:02:34,159
Over time, they become good at switching languages and ignoring the ones they don't need in a conversation.

43
00:02:34,799 --> 00:02:38,879
Scientists think that juggling several languages is good for you.

44
00:02:39,359 --> 00:02:43,599
If you juggle several things, that means you deal with all of them at the same time.

45
00:02:44,400 --> 00:02:48,560
Frederick describes being a polyglot as a brain workout.

46
00:02:48,560 --> 00:02:52,079
This means it's exercise for your brain that can make it stronger.

47
00:02:52,719 --> 00:02:54,959
Now, Hannah, I don't know about you.

48
00:02:54,959 --> 00:03:00,000
When I was younger and languages just seemed like another subject at school,

49
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:02,159
I didn't really care so much.

50
00:03:02,159 --> 00:03:07,039
But when I worked abroad later in life, I was much more motivated and found it easier.

51
00:03:07,039 --> 00:03:07,680
How about you?

52
00:03:08,479 --> 00:03:10,400
Quite the opposite, actually.

53
00:03:10,400 --> 00:03:14,800
I did find it easier to learn languages at school and university.

54
00:03:14,800 --> 00:03:18,879
But I didn't have to learn these languages out of necessity.

55
00:03:18,879 --> 00:03:25,200
But my colleague, Victoria Unmongkunda, she's a presenter and a journalist on the BBC World Service.

56
00:03:25,200 --> 00:03:26,319
She did.

57
00:03:26,319 --> 00:03:29,680
She speaks five languages and she understands eight.

58
00:03:29,680 --> 00:03:36,400
And she learnt those languages because her family moved from Rwanda to Kenya and then to Norway

59
00:03:36,400 --> 00:03:37,759
when she was a teenager.

60
00:03:37,759 --> 00:03:41,359
Victoria says she was able to pick up Norwegian quite easily.

61
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:47,039
If you pick up a skill, it means you learn it usually by being in the environment where that

62
00:03:47,039 --> 00:03:49,359
thing happens rather than being taught.

63
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:54,479
But Victoria's parents found it much harder to learn Norwegian.

64
00:03:54,479 --> 00:03:57,199
Let's hear what Vic said on the What in the World podcast.

65
00:03:58,239 --> 00:04:03,439
First of all, you're having them coming to a new culture completely from everything they've

66
00:04:03,520 --> 00:04:04,400
ever known.

67
00:04:04,400 --> 00:04:05,439
The language is new.

68
00:04:06,159 --> 00:04:07,919
These are people in their 50s.

69
00:04:07,919 --> 00:04:12,479
You know, but they they soldier on because if you want to work, if you want to live there,

70
00:04:12,479 --> 00:04:14,079
you have to learn and they did.

71
00:04:14,079 --> 00:04:18,720
It wasn't easy, but I think also with that kids, we picked it up quite quickly.

72
00:04:18,720 --> 00:04:22,240
So if they were making a mistake, who were also helping them along the way.

73
00:04:22,240 --> 00:04:26,079
So it kind of a way of paying back, you helped us get to this, you know,

74
00:04:26,079 --> 00:04:28,959
to keep our mother tongue in here, we are going to help you.

75
00:04:28,959 --> 00:04:33,040
Victoria's parents found it difficult to learn Norwegian in their 50s,

76
00:04:33,040 --> 00:04:34,480
but they soldiered on.

77
00:04:34,480 --> 00:04:38,000
They continued doing something even though it was difficult.

78
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:41,040
And I love that the family helped each other with their languages, Hannah.

79
